,"Ampton, Suffolk, England":"Ampton, Suffolk, England","England":"England","Chediston, Suffolk, England":"Chediston, Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cockett","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","in Lancashire and Yorkshire: habitational name from Cocket in Rathmell (near Giggleswick, Yorkshire).","in southeastern England: variant of <b>Cackett</b>, a habitational name from Cacket's Farm in Chelsfield (Kent), which was earlier recorded as <i>Caldecote</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Cocklin","meanings":["English: from an Old French and Middle English personal name <i>Cokelin</i>, a French double diminutive of   Cocke   2.","Perhaps also an Americanized form of Swiss German and South German <b>Köchlin</b>, <b>Koechlin</b>, or <b>Köchling</b>, all diminutives of   Koch  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":25,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York